Visual Description (3D Plot Interpretation)
Imagine a 3D coordinate system with axes:

X-axis: t‚ÇÅ (first time)
Y-axis: t‚ÇÇ (second time)
Z-axis: x (spatial)
The two null geodesics appear as straight lines rising from the origin in the positive t‚ÇÅ‚Äìt‚ÇÇ quadrant, tilted at different angles.
The steeper line (v = 1.50) has a larger t‚ÇÇ component ‚Üí more "motion" along the second time direction.
The time-like path is flatter in the t‚ÇÅ‚Äìt‚ÇÇ plane and rises more slowly along x ‚Üí it stays inside the hyperbolic light cone.
The light-cone boundary looks like two opposing hyperbolas in the t‚ÇÅ‚Äìt‚ÇÇ plane (projected along x).

Does This Fit Your "time moves forward with set velocity in 2D space" Idea?
Yes ‚Äî quite naturally:

You can define "forward time" by restricting to trajectories where both dt‚ÇÅ/dœÑ > 0 and dt‚ÇÇ/dœÑ > 0 (future-directed in both times).
A fixed velocity ratio v = dt‚ÇÇ/dt‚ÇÅ becomes a conserved quantity along geodesics (especially null ones) due to the flat metric.
This ratio can be set by initial conditions or topological constraints in your larger theory (e.g., derived from G‚ÇÇ holonomy or lattice properties).
In the full 24+3D bulk, the (2,1) block could be a local coordinate patch where emergent 1D time arises from projecting or averaging along a preferred direction in the (t‚ÇÅ, t‚ÇÇ) plane.

Quick Code Snippet You Can Run Locally
If you want to experiment yourself (requires matplotlib and numpy):
Pythonimport numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

tau = np.linspace(0, 10, 200)

# Null geodesic example
v = 0.5           # fixed velocity ratio dt2/dt1
a = 1.0
b = v * a
norm = np.sqrt(a**2 + b**2)
t1 = a * tau
t2 = b * tau
x  = norm * tau

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.plot(t1, t2, x, label=f'null geodesic v = {v}', color='blue', lw=2)

# Add your own second trajectory, time-like path, etc.
