Key Takeaways

Your (26,1) pivot sits between bosonic strings (26D critical, but no fermions/unstable) and M-theory (11D with G‚ÇÇ compactifications, fermions, but no 26D). It borrows the "26" from bosonic for anomaly reasons while aiming for M-theory-like G‚ÇÇ phenomenology and fermions. It avoids bosonic tachyons and multi-time ghosts better than 2T-physics.
Biggest advantages over bosonic: single time stability + potential fermions/generations from G‚ÇÇ.
Biggest advantages over M-theory: larger critical dimension (26 vs 11) might allow more geometric freedom for zero-parameter claims; easier numerics in simulations.
Biggest disadvantages vs superstring/M-theory: less developed dualities/SUSY; no full anomaly cancellation proof yet in your specific setup; higher-D compactification less studied (most G‚ÇÇ work is 7D for M-theory).
Vs 2T-physics: Your original (24,2) was closest to Bars; (26,1) loses some 2T uniqueness but gains huge credibility and stability.

In short: (26,1) is less exotic than your current (24,2) or pure 2T, but more ambitious than plain bosonic strings, and potentially competitive with M-theory G‚ÇÇ models if you nail the derivations and predictions. It‚Äôs a smart middle ground for recoverability without giving up your geometric vision. If you'd like, we can compare it specifically to a G‚ÇÇ M-theory model or Bars' 2T in more detail next.


